column27: reframe
fgjfjgfjgjfjfgjfgkfkgffgkfkfkfkfkfkfkfkfkfkfgjjgjjgjjgjgjgjgfjfgggjgjgfjgfj

You can replace the things that you lost in your wallet, and it shouldn't be difficult to do. I think this experience will lead you to be more careful of your things and make sure that you're not forgetful. This isn't a permanent situation, and it isn't that big of a deal.

I know this is a tough setback, but the situation could be worse. You could have gotten robbed for it and ultimately hurt or killed. Try not to think about how long it will take you to replace it, maybe some good things will happen along the way. The situation cannot get any worse and will only go up from here.

Oh I'm sorry this happened to you. How did you lose your wallet? At least you didn't have a ton of cash in there. Most things can be taken care of online these days too. Are there any techniques you can use to help you remember things? Retrace your steps and call all the places you visited when you had your wallet, maybe someone turned it in.

It sucks now but you were going to have to get new cards and drivers licenses eventually anyway.  Just think of this as having to update them a bit earlier than you expected but now you will get a few more years added to when they would have expired before.  You can use this to help remember for the future too so you won't lose things again.
i am so sorry this happened to you. I know what it feels like the same exact thing happened to me. Keep your head up things will get better and enjoy the rest of you day!

I know how it is to lose a wallet. It's happened to me a couple of times in my life. Even though it's a terrible thing and very stressful to get it back or get all your credit cards and license again, I think you can view it as a growing experience. Perhaps it will teach you to be more careful next time and try to always keep tabs on it. I would view it as a positive situation since you can get a new wallet (one that you really like a lot more and that is fashionable with more pockets in it) and get fresh, new cards to carry around. You will learn to be more careful, as well as have a nice new wallet that you can cherish and put all your things in. It will remind you of what happened to your old wallet and remind you to always look after it. Get a really nice wallet and make sure to take good care of it.

Aww. That stinks man! Im so sorry! Im sorry you lost your wallet but look at it this way, now you get to replace your liscense and get a new photo taken for that. You've lost so much weight this year and you look great it was about time for you to get that new photo!

I understand how frustrating it can be to misplace belongings . Do not beat yourself over it, because we are all human and make mistakes. Stressing yourself about the situation is natural, but it does not change the conflict. Just move forward I promise things will get better

This is the sort of thing that can happen when you're so busy. There probably aren't that many things in your wallet that will be that hard to replace, and most of them will come in the mail. So it's not something you have to spend a lot of time worrying about. It could also help you save money, since you can't really spend anything for a while. It happens to all of us, so don't think poorly of yourself.

The situation isn't a long lasting situation. The matter will be fixed in a few days, once you get situated with calling the people required to get new cards and a license. This situation also will allow you to learn to keep track of your wallet better, as it is a situation that is inconvenient.

I'm sorry that you lost your wallet, that is a huge inconvenience, but it happens. On the plus side, it's far easier to freeze and replace your debit and credit cards than it's been in the past. It's still a hassle, but it'll help you rebuild faster. Maybe someone will find it and return it to you.

That would be incredibly frustrating to lose your wallet, and I can understand why you are upset.  Try not to be so hard on yourself.  We all are forgetful at times.  Its possible that a person even found your wallet and is currently trying to track you down.

The wallet has been lost. It is important to accept loss when it occurs. That means, don't dwell on the loss, accept that it has happened and move on. Don't think too much about replacing everything. Just replace what is important, cancel card numbers, etc. Remember that this is also a chance to get new cards and a new wallet. So maybe it will help symbolize a new stage in your life. You also learned a lesson about being careful, and not forgetful. This is an important lesson. Maybe because of this event, you may remember something far more important. For instance, you may remember to put your parking brake in, preventing a loss far more catastrophic than a lost wallet.
My partner lost everything with his wallet most likely including credit cards and ID.

I've had a lot of headaches. I get them a lot during the month during times of stress. Drinking doesn't help things and makes things worse. If you need to drink to relax, though, that's okay. I think drinking is a good way to unwind after a long hard day. Perhaps since you haven't been sleeping, you can devote your energy to other things that are productive when you aren't sleeping. Not sleeping gives you time to do other things, either productive things or things that you might enjoy. Take the time to do those things and then maybe you'll fall asleep soon after. Just view the lack of sleep as a positive thing and extra time to get things done.

Look, drinking to help you relax and sleep at night is never a good solution. Finding better and safer alternatives will surely work for you. I like to run at night a few hours before bed, this helps me relax much more. If you continue to do this, just be aware you could potentially develop a drinking problem and become reliant on alcohol to help you get to sleep. Maybe you cannot sleep because something is on your mind every night. Learn from the situation, if your sleeping habits are disrupted enough for you to resort to drinking before bed, then there is a much larger underlying problem going on. FIND IT! FIX IT!

I'm very sorry to hear that you haven't been sleeping well lately.  I get headaches a lot when I'm feeling dehydrated, which might be what you're going through if you aren't getting enough water along with the alcohol.  This isn't a permanent situation and it might help to make a list to consider what is keeping you awake in the first place.  This way you can focus on improving those areas of concern to help you finally get some natural rest.

It sounds like the headache is a sign that you might need to find a different way to relax. Whether it's because you're drinking, or because you aren't sleeping well, your body is trying to tell you something. Maybe try to think of what's keeping you from relaxing and getting a good night's sleep.

I understand the effects sleep deprivation can have, itג€™s like a domino effect in your life that makes even simple tasks very demanding. But thatג€™s the thing, dominoes have to stop from somewhere. Instead of drinking to relax, you can find something else worth your time that wonג€™t make your life miserable. I know it may seem hard, but you will greatly appreciate yourself for making such a responsible decision.

I know it may seem like a big deal that you still have your headache, but at least you got a decent rest last night. There are many options for you, such as taking aspirin. Also, sleep is very important for you to function. If you are having trouble sleeping, then you can look into the many natural sleep-aids that exist.

I understand this all too well. However, there are alternatives to drinking that can help you fall asleep, completely natural and safe too. Melatonin is what we naturally produce that makes us tired. They sell melatonin tablets, which again is what we naturally  produce to make us tired, and they are completely safe to take.  Far safer than medications like ambien. It could possibly help, and I hope you'll look into them. You can get them in a variety of doses, and I myself take 5mg on nights i struggle to fall asleep. Getting proper sleep, and avoiding the alcholol to help you relax, should help with your headaches. This is not permanent,  and there is an easy and safr solution I encourage you to look into if you have doubts about its safety.
Dear study partner,

This may be the reason you need to improve your sleep habits.  This isn't working so it's probably time to find something that does.  It could be because you're stressed and need to do something about that or for some other reason.  What matters though is that you can improve your sleep patterns in a better way and then not have to worry about drinking causing you issues.
Dear Friend,
This isn't that bad and can be fixed by going to the doctor or trying different remedies. The situation isn't permanent and it will be over soon.

Sleeping problems are part of being human, everyone goes through them at some point during their life. Always remember that things could be a lot worse. Some people don't get any sleep at all, and are forced to go about their day without any sleep. Your headache could also be unrelated to the drinking, it is also something that could be worse. Many people deal with chronic headaches on a daily basis. Hopefully you will find a way to deal with these inconveniences and get on with your life.
Chances are the headache will go away in time. There is no way to know that the drinking is causing the problem so there's no need to worry about it.
Ugh, headaches are terrible. Do you need anything? What is going on that has you stressed and not sleeping well?

It seems like you've identified the most likely cause of your problem, which is the first step to solving it. To avoid future headaches like this, reduce your alcohol consumption, and also increase the amount of water you drink when drinking alcohol, as dehydration is the chief cause of head pain following a drinking session. Other causes include disruption of glucose metabolism and reduced fasting blood sugar, so it can also be beneficial to consume something sweet when drinking to reduce inflammation and vasodilation that can increase the symptoms of head pain.

Oh, you must be under a lot of stress. Perhaps there is another coping mechanism you could try instead of drinking. Drinking can cause dehydration which might give you a headache. Maybe try something like reading or meditating. I find yoga to be super relaxing. It's good that you recognize your drinking may be a problem. It might help you to talk about whatever it is that's making it hard to go to sleep. Are you upset about something, or worried about something? It will be okay, don't worry.
It's not necessarily due to having a drink.  Headaches are also commonly caused by diet, stress, or by not drinking enough water.  So there may be something else going on that causes the headaches.

Yeah, headaches aren't any fun. I get headaches quite a bit, and I'm never really sure what's causing them. Rather than the drinking being the cause, maybe the headache is from not getting enough sleep. Once your sleeping improves, your headache might too. I hope it goes away soon!

I know how it feels to have some rough sleep at night but often I've found that alcohol actually leads to less restful nights. If you haven't given it a shot I would say try some melatonin at night to help get you to sleep. Luckily our body does catch up on the sleep we need, and your headache will go away.

Hey!! You're probably just a little dehydrated. Im sure if you up your water intake during the day your headache will go away. Perhaps instead of using alcohol to relax at night you can try melatonin or dream water which are sleep supplements.

I have also been drinking more often than I usually do. Having a glass of wine or two before bed helps me stay asleep longer. I have been very stressed and I think this is why I have been drinking more often. Handling stresses should be easier and more natural but sometimes a "quick fix" is needed. I completely understand your situation.
Hey! Keep you head up things can only go up from here. Remember there is someone always out there that cares about you
The situation can be improved easily, if you reduce the drinking it will most likely go away. You have to find another way to relax, as excessive drinking wonג€™t do you good.
I can see how that could be a result of drinking. It's not so bad though because you can use this experience as a tool. In the future you'll remember it and maybe not drink.

We all have our vices ro help us at the end of a hard day. Though they may temporairly relieve these stresses, sometimes the next days they may bring new peoblems (your headache) Luckily, you're not alone! Maybe next time add a couple more glasses a water, it'll help with the headache. Maybe switch out the drink with some CBD.

It does seem like you're worried. I wonder if there's something else you could do instead of drinking to relax. Maybe you could try other methods of relaxation? There are many that people use, including meditation, hot tea, and even melatonin. If you're worried, maybe you could focus on changing the behavior to something that feels better to you.
I get headaches regularly, they really suck. I wouldn't worry too much about it unless it lasts for a few days, sometimes a bad headache just sticks around for a bit.

First, it's a headache. It's an annoying problem, but nothing that can't improve with time. If you're getting it because you're drinking, then it should go away if you cut down on your alcohol. It's not something to get too worried about, because it doesn't sound like you're suffering from a migraine or any other crippling problem. This is merely a headache that is caused by an easily fixable behavior. Maybe you can learn something from it. What is causing your sleep to be less restful than it could otherwise be? If you could fix that, then you might not have to drink as much, meaning the problem will probably disappear.

hey, Sorry that you have been having a problem watching to much TV. I had the same problem and it worked itself out for me so I am sure it will for you to. Just keep your head up it is not that big of a deal to begin with.

It's a good thing that you realize this is a problem. Most people do things like this and never think twice about it. Since you've realized that it is something you'd like to fix you can start taking steps to fix it. Especially since you're already disappointed in yourself. It means that you're looking to change.

You just need to set reminders for yourself to stay on track. This isn't a permanent situation and you can teach yourself to have more self-control. Take small steps and set goals so you can prioritize what's important.

Maybe you should consider a different alternative for relaxing before bed. Reading in bed always helps me get tired pretty fast. Do not get down on yourself for something so insignificant. Think of ways to become more disciplined, not just in sleeping but also in life. You can learn something about yourself from this and that is that you need to be more disciplined with yourself! You can only blame yourself and should not loathe the situation. It is not as bad as you think, things could be much worse than not getting a goods night sleep. Goodluck!

You have your whole life to sleep. Sleeping would be great, yes, but so is watching TV. It's great that you can make time for yourself to watch TV. Maybe watch more TV and then you will relax and fall asleep soon afterward. You'll have plenty of time to sleep when you're dead, anyway, so you might as well enjoy your free time. Enjoy the TV because you'll never know when you may not be able to anymore.
Is there a reason you decided to stay up late. Maybe you could try exercising in the evening to make you sleepy before bed so you don't stay up so late.

Staying up late watching TV is a pretty harmless vice. If it helps you relax, it maybe isn't such a bad thing. If it begins to affect your health, mental or physical, maybe try to set a schedule or guidelines for it so you can relax AND get a good night's sleep.

First of all, this problem isn't nearly as bad as it seems. All it takes is some self control to remedy. You are disappointed in yourself, and feel pathetic because deep down you know you should be able to better control yourself. But instead of obsessing over it, why not simply act? If you notice that you're watching too much TV, turn it off. Close your Netflix app or turn off your streaming player if you have to. Even if you spend too much time, you'll feel better when you know that you are re-establishing self control by cutting yourself off. This is so doable that it couldn't be simpler. It's a really easy thing to do.

As long as you enjoy TV and aren't too tired because of staying up to watch TV, it doesn't seem to me there is any reason to for you to be disappointed in yourself. I think you are being too hard on yourself.

column14: I volunteer to take part in this research
column27: The good thing is you could change this virtually whenever you really want. We all have moments we feel disappointed in ourselves, but you are.not.doing anything that can cause serious damage, yet. Just turn the t.v. off early one night this week, and get some rest before it affects your health. Best of luck.

You shouldn't feel too bad about this. A lot of people stay up late to watch TV. Simply take this day and use it as a teachable moment. What have you learned from doing this? There is no reason to be disappointed in yourself. I'm sure you've made other mistakes before. All that making a mistake does is show that you are human and you are not perfect.

It is okay to stay up late sometimes, maybe just try to not make a habit out of it. It seems like a very fixable issue, just try and keep a positive outlook on the situation.

Sometimes, we want to do something more than what is normal. You know it's normal to go to bed at a reasonable time, yet something is drawing you towards the tv. Maybe this is an opportunity to try something new! Sleep is a necessity, but nobody ever said that you had to do it all at night. Nobody ever said you had to do all your sleep in one go. Your concern is that you're not getting enough sleep. Take a nap! Even 20 minutes of rest can help refresh your mind to perform better than you would otherwise. After you've tried that for a few days, you should be able to acknowledge which one you like better, and then it will be easier to go back to your old routine if you were to choose that one.

Everyone stays up late watching TV sometimes. Can you think of why you might be doing this? Are you hooked on a show or are you just bored? I have to set an alarm sometimes to remind myself it's time for bed or I'll stay up past midnight watching the same show.

You know admitting you have a problem is the first step to solving it. You know you don't like this that means you can do something about it. Think of how easy it is to make incremental improvements too for this. You can cut back on one 30 minutes show at first. Or even just not finish the final show you were planning on watching if it's not interesting. Then you can work towards watching even less at night, maybe shift more to the daytime or weekends if possible if you still want to watch tv. You can also slowly find other things to replace them with at night that will make it easier to fall asleep like reading or some other hobby.

Staying up late and watching TV is not a big deal. Everyone does this from time to time and they are just fine the next day. You may feel a bit sluggish the next day but I assure you, you'll be fine, and life will go on. There is some good humor on late at night, or perhaps some classic movies that you have never seen. Staying up late and watching TV will never have a huge negative effect on your life, you will enjoy it most of the time and it's not something you should be very concerned about.

Dear study partner,
Please consider why TV keeps you up at night and what you could do to minimize your viewing time so that you can be better prepared for resting. Turn that disappointment upside down and use it as motivation to do better by yourself and your health. I hope you get better sleep tonight!

If you are not getting tired enough to sleep while watching TV, then maybe your body just isn't ready to sleep. This probably isn't permanent. This could also give you the opportunity to catch up on your favorite TV shows or start watching a new show you've been interested in but haven't had the time to watch.

I’m sorry to hear that you haven’t been sleeping as much as you’d like. I also tend to stay up later than I should in order to catch up on my shows. Would it help to set aside time during the weekend for certain shows so that you aren’t so tired during the week? A little missed sleep hurts the next day but try to remember how tired you felt the next time you tell yourself “just one more show.”

I know it can be so easy to leave the TV on late at night. It's a simple way to "relax." But if you've noticed that it's actually getting in the way of real relaxation, maybe there are some changes you could make. Have you considered other ways to relax that don't include screen time? Maybe you could take the opportunity to really think about ways to take care of yourself and create a nice bedtime ritual that doesn't include TV. You don't even have to go cold turkey, but just turning the TV off 5-10 minutes earlier every night could make a difference. Good luck!

I know that it can be hard to get some rest at night, especially with all the distractions in the world. Missing a bit of sleep isn't really too bad though. I think at the end of the day you're the only one disappointed in yourself. Chances are most others don't really notice it.

Sure, sleeping is probably the best way to relax, but watching TV really isn't too bad either. As long as you're not doing jumping jacks or some other vigorous activity, I really think it's okay. How much energy could you possibly be using? Plus, it's a great way to catch up on any shows you've been missing, rather than stressing about when you'll find the time to watch them. As long as you still feel rested the next day, I wouldn't worry about it too much. If you get tired enough, you may even start to fall asleep right in front of the TV!

I've had similar problems in the past, and the real solution is to develop the discipline necessary to avoid repeating the inappropriate behavior. That sounds easy, but can take a long time to cultivate. Until you are able to cultivate the behavior you need to correct the problem, however, it's important to realize that, in the grand scheme of things, staying up late to watch a television program you enjoy isn't the worst thing a person can do. As long as you are meeting your other obligations, you shouldn't feel guilty about how you choose to spend your free time.

Honestly that's not so bad. Think of it this way, you got to do something enjoyable and it seems like you're going to stop doing it. That means your got to have a bit of cake but you'll also get to have the good creamy ice cream of sleep. No worries!

Your problem is just a temporary one that can be fixed in a short time. You have to push yourself to restricting your TV usage late at night as it effects you during the daytime. You'll feel better once you adapt to doing so.

Perhaps the TV is not the root cause of you feeling down. It certainly could be, and you could experiment with changing your behavior to see if it fixes it. I think that this is certainly resolvable, and that you shouldn't get down on yourself. Tons of people watch too much TV, and getting down about it will keep you in the same habits. Keep your eyes on your goal!

Even though you are really upset with yourself, I promise I have faith in you to even acknowledge your shortcomings . We all do things we regret, and I believe It will get better once you try a little to sleep. Drink tea and down the lights low in your sleeping space , and you may have a better night rest.

I feel like if you stopped worrying about it and just do it you would feel alot better about yourself. I generally have lots of things to do but I tend not to worry about them and everything works out in the end. Keep your head up you got this.

The concept of "running out of time" is just that - a concept. We do not own time. Time is not something that you can physically lose. What you must do is change your perception of time. Find a way to prioritize everything in your life by level of importance, and do what is the most important task first. 

Everything that needs to be done will find a way. You need to separate what needs to be done from what you want to be done. Learn to accept that life is never finished. Take a deep breath, and realize just how harmful stress can be for your overall health.

Ask yourself if all the things you "have" to get done are worth the emotional and mental toll on your health? Probably not.

At least you aren't bored. It helps to be busy because it keeps us occupied. It helps our minds grow and it helps us be less depressed. Having a lot of work is not necessarily a bad thing. There is plenty of time to finish things, too. Perhaps put other things aside to create more time (like hobbies or time with family). It's important to get work done. It makes us better people. It's great that you are so busy and have so many things to do. That way, you won't be bored or sad.
I find for me the easiest way to tackle a lot of work is to break it up into much smaller tasks. This little task make it seem less daunting and easier to tackle to me.

Try to relax. What's going to happen if you don't finish all the work on time? Can you get an extension? Is there someone who can help you? Take it one step at a time and try not to worry too much. Just do the best you can. Things will get better once this all passes.

You still have time. Make a plan, figure out what needs to be done first, and start from there. Do what you can to whittle down the amount of work you have to do and get the most important stuff out of the way. Unfortunately, just getting the work done is the only thing you can do to help with the stress, and the longer you wait the worse it will become. Make some tea, put on some soothing music, and figure out where to begin.

Start by breaking it down into smaller pieces. Don't worry about the finish line for now just focus on the starting line. Get done what you can, you can always make something better by doing something about it rather than avoiding it because you don't think you can finish. Think about things you might be able to put off if you can't get them done for now.

Take a breather and reassess your situation. Your issue could be way worse. You might need to sacrifice some of your time so you can get caught up. Don't spend your time doing anything else, just also do not forget to take care of yourself in the process. This is not the end of the world and it is not near as bad as you think. Things could be way worse. Manage your time better and it will help you be prepared for similar situations in the future. Learn from it and remind yourself things could be much worse than they are for you.

column14: I volunteer to take part in this research.
column27: I am actually in a similar situation now! Sometimes it's nice to know you're not alone. When it comes to completing things you need to prioritize and make a list, even if it's just mentally, and work on each one; one step at time. If each task should take an hour work on it for an hour, and done or not move on to the next. Some may take longer than an hour(using this time frame as a theroretical one), but some will likely also take less. Once you have gotten through your list attend to the ones you did not get finished in the specified time allotment you gave yourself to dedicate to it. AND, most of all, breathe. You'll get through it.

I would tell him that he should focus on the more important tasks first and work his way through the things that he needs to do. He should ask others for help so that he can complete his work on time. The situation isn't permanent and he could manage his time better so that he isn't feeling stressed.

When deadlines approach, I also tend to get stressed out. Sometimes, it might help to make a list of things left so that way you can visualize what still needs to get done. It is very satisfying to check items off of that list too.

It's natural to feel overwhelmed when the responsibilities pile up and the amount of time dwindles down. Sometimes, it may cause us to overthink how bad a given consequence is. Sit down, take a moment, and consider seriously what the cost of each deadline is. Can some be pushed back? Can some be assigned to other people? These situations will pop up frequently in life, so the important lesson is to learn how to prepare for them in a way that you can deal with them without feeling so inundated.

Try not to focus on how little time you have and instead think about how to make the best use of your time. There's nothing you can do about the things you can't control so let go of those types of thoughts.
Think about how good you will feel once this work is accomplished. You will have plenty of time to relax afterward, knowing that you overcame the feat.

I understand the stresses of feeling like you will run out of time when you have a lot to do. That said though you're in a good place if you have a lot to do. They are all things that will ultimately move your life forward and are things that will better you. I would suggest making a list and decide what you need to do by priority.

The thing to remember in situations like this is that it is important to focus on the positive of the situation. It's true that you're suffering from work related stress, but the only way you're able to have work related stress is because you have employment. If you didn't have any work to do, you certainly wouldn't feel any stress about the amount you needed to get accomplished, but this would only be replaced by a different stressor, the lack of things to do. When we accept that all of life is suffering, it makes it easier to put these sorts of unpleasant stresses into perspective.

You have a lot of work to do. But that means that you are important, in that people depend on you. When you have work to do, it means that others need you to succeed in order for them to succeed.

Not all tasks are the same. Can some of them be put off? Focus on the most important tasks. If some less important stuff misses the deadline, don't sweat it.

Also, you can reduce your amount of stress by simply getting down to work and doing it. As you check off tasks, your workload gets significantly lighter.

Maybe you can talk to your boss or your family to figure out ways to reduce your workload. Maybe spend more time, say, on classes instead of working on projects? Maybe ask for some brainstorming or "cool down" time? Google allows this for their employees, and they've grown to be one of the biggest companies...

It's so easy to feel overwhelmed these days. It seems like there just isn't enough time in the day. I often stress out when I feel like things are piling up, but once I actually dive in and start working on my to-do list, I realize it's not as bad as I was expecting. In fact, I try to see these situations as opportunities to work on my organizational skills and my ability to focus. Every time I can cross something off my list, I feel a sense of accomplishment. And once I get everything done, I know I'll be better prepared the next time I have a lot of things to do. Hang in there!

The stress you are feeling will help you preform better and get the work done in time. Everyone feels overwhelmed from time to time, you will get through it. Having a firm deadline has been proven to help people with the quality of their work and the amount of time it takes. It is the best way to prevent procrastination. You can also imagine how good you are going to feel when all the work is done, it will be a great feeling.

While you may feel pressured, this feeling can also be a good stressor. The sense that you have a lot of things to accomplish and not much time to do them in will force you to focus, and help to eliminate unnecessary tasks. Use this as an opportunity to really examine your workload, and you will likely be able to discern what's really important. You may still feel short at time, but keep track of what you accomplish and you will likely be surprised.

This is the kind of situation that feels bad in the moment, but will eventually turn into something good. Once you finish that work you'll feel a really great sense of accomplishment. This stress isn't permanent, it isn't something that will continue forever, so it should be a bit easier to get through.
Take a deep breath. Think of it this way, you can only do so much. If you don't get the work done then the world will still turn.

Do not worry, you have a lot of work that is due but it is not a big deal, you are lucky to have so much work, just look at it that way, you could be in a worse situation and not have any work to due. That would mean no money though. 

This is not permanent and you will probably get a few weeks off after its all done. Next time just manage your time better and do not procrastinate I say this because I do it all the time, haha.

Take a breathe and step back. Getting stressed happens to all of us. The best we can do is just take it one moment at a time. Looking at it piece by piece will make u feel more accomplished. We all get swept up when we feel things getting out of control, at these moments we csn refoxus ourswlves and really do a good job.

That certainly sounds like a very stressful situation. Is there anything you can do to alleviate your stress? Perhaps talk to someone about getting some support? Or maybe accept that some of it might not get done on time and reprioritize your goals? Such a stressful situation isn't going to help you get the work done quickly, maybe it's time to reach out to get help for improving it.

I am sorry to hear about your mentor. Perhaps his passing can be seen as a good thing since you can view it as him passing the baton to you. Since he is gone, it is now up to you to carry on his wishes and teachings. He lives through you and what he taught you as a mentor. Now he is free and in a better place and even though you won't see him again, he will always be with you and his teachings will always be with you, as well as the memories you shared together. You have grown as a person and I'm sure, wherever your mentor is now, he is looking down on you and smiling.

I know it is one of the hardest things in this life to lost someone you love who is close to you, it sucks and I understand. It's bad but it gets better, obviously you cannot bring them back but you can do good in their name, you can be kind to their family and offer to help around. Look at the bright side, they were your mentor and gave you the priceless gift of knowledge, something that is so precious that he will forever live inside you. Whatever does not kill you makes you stronger, and this is definitely one of those situations, there is nothing you could have done and the fact that you care so much means you are a really good person. Do not worry, you will learn from this experience and grow from it, from this tragedy learn to love your loved ones and appreciate them,

You should think of all the things that you learned and be happy that you were able to spend time with your mentor. You will feel better when you realize all that you’ve done and they wouldn’t want you to feel sad.

I know that your mentor has had a very meaningful impact in your life, and he will always be a part of you. However, you must take his teachings and continue his legacy in your life by taking his practices to heart and keeping him alive via your actions. God bless and it will get better
It'll be hard at first but it'll get better with time. It's good that you have positive experiences to remember your mentor by.
I know it seems tough right now having a fresh loss but it does get easier. I know it may not seem that way but it really does.

column14: I volunteer to take part in this research
column27: While it is sad, death is a natural thing. Grief comes in waves one moment you will be fine and in the.next it hits you like a ton of bricks. Time does help, amd the immediate sharp pain goes away. I am sure your mentor would want you to celebrate the life they had, and remember the moments you had together with a smile on your face. You are learning a very valuable lesson in how to deal with grief and death. Always remember the people who you care about, that pass away, would want you too look back and remember them with a smile on your face. They would not want to see you sad, so remember them, grieve if/when you must, but try to remember that they would want you to push on, be happy, and lead the life your own life to the fullest. This could also allow you to reflect on how you want to be remembered and help steer your life down the path you truly want to follow.

I'm so sorry to hear about your mentor. I can't imagine how you feel right now. Try to remember the learning experiences you've had with this person. That's the best way to honor their memory. I'm sure they were at peace knowing that they had such a positive influence on others' lives. That's the most any of us could want when leaving this world.

It's important to remember your memories with your mentor, and what they taught you. They may be gone, but they clearly had a lasting impact on you and your life. Be grateful for what you learned, and pay it forward.

Your mentor is in a better place now. While it hurts a ton to lose someone close to you, you should try to remember the happy times, as long as you remember them they are never really gone. Death is the last part of life and everyone has to deal with it eventually. You should always remember how lucky you were to have such a great mentor in your life, I'm sure you learned a lot.
I am so sorry for what happened to you. I never lost someone I cared for so I can't imagine how you feel. I feel you head up things will get better with time.

You are off to a good start by remembering what your mentor has taught you and the relationship the both of you had. Try to never forget those times. As corny as it sounds, your mentor would be happy if you stayed positive. You can still grieve, just try to stay connected with yourself at the same time. Although your mentor is gone you still have valuable lessons you have learned from them and you should allow yourself to continue to grow from those lessons. Let yourself mourn, but try to be happy while you do. Your mentor would want that.

I know it's hard to think about your mentor passing away, but death is a rather unfortunate side effect of life. None of use make it out of here alive. Instead, try to focus on the good times that you shared with this person and consider yourself blessed for having such a meaningful connection with another person in your life.

Death is never easy, but our loved ones never really leave us. We keep them alive in our hearts.

I'm sorry to hear that your mentor passed away. It's always hard to deal with the loss of a person, but it's definitely good that you have a lot of memories and can think back to a lot of good times. I would say take this opportunity to reach out to others that have touched your life and let them know they have while they're still around so that it can help you in the future.

Mentors are meant to serve to guide us, to shape us into the people we are meant to be. Mentors live on in the lessons that they've given, and the path that they've directed you towards. It is good to mourn them. They were important to you, and it is the greatest compliment to a person's life that you pause at their passing. Remember what you shared, and live to bring meaning to the lessons they have taught.

It's really unfortunate that someone so close has passed away, but I think that it's a great opportunity to really reflect on this person's significance in your life and make sure that you're honoring your relationship. Perhaps there's someone in your life that you could assume a similar role with, or there may be opportunities to enact some of the mentorship that you've been hesitating on. There are many opportunities to continue making your mentor a blessing to your life and to others, and while he or she may not be there in person, the lessons and experiences shared from your mentor can live on, with your help.

I'm sorry to hear about your mentor passing away. Clearly they were important to you, and I'm sure they would be touched to know how deeply their passing has affected you. It's completely natural to have trouble accepting what has happened. It might take quite a while for you to accept their passing, but's nice that you have so many fond memories to remember your mentor by. This will help you get through such a tough time.

Even though your mentor passed away, those experiences that you carry won't ever go away. You'll carry them with you, and the other people effected by them probably have similar feelings. You aren't alone. The main thing is to realize how special it is that you got to have those experiences, and try to focus on those good times that you had.

Let's be honest, the death of your mentor is a terrible loss. I'm not going to sugar coat it. But now that they have passed away, it's important to remember the lessons that they gave you. The best way to honor their life is to remember their guidance, and possibly write it down before you forget it. Try to keep as much of their memory intact as possible. This way you can preserve their contribution to your life.

This situation, while harsh, is a crucible that not only teaches you how to deal with loss but also the loss of advice and guidance. Often times there won't be someone there to help you out or tell you what to do; you have to do it on your own. How will you handle the situation? Try to see how you are handling things right now, and remember your mentor's advice throughout.

Eventually you will come out of this a better person. It will take some time; don't rush yourself. But do try to remember as much of your mentor's advice as possible and put it in to action.
You will never forget the experiences you had together. Your mentor's teachings will live on through you.

I'm sorry for your loss. It is hard to lose someone you were close to, whether or not you've been with them recently. I hope that you can continue to find gratitude for your time with that person, and that you find peace in their passing. Would it be helpful to process their death by connecting with some part of their legacy?

I'm so sorry about the loss of your mentor. It is so hard when someone important to us passes away. It is so great that you were lucky enough to have a mentor and I bet your mentor appreciated and cared for you as well. What a special relationship you had. You will always have that experience and those memories to hold dear. Maybe one day you can carry on your mentor's legacy by being a mentor to someone yourself.

It's good you can think about how they've impacted your life. Now that you have that in mind though you can think about trying to spread what they've taught you to others and be a mentor to them like they were to you. Just like they were significant for you and left an impact it's now your time to do the same.

It is always unfortunate to deal with the loss of a person who is important to us. The only thing to do is to remember that the advice you were given by your mentor was important. The best thing to do now is to use what you learned from your mentor to help other people, to both live up to the example your mentor set you, as well as to help preserve some small part of their influence in the world. By doing this, you can think of the death less as an ending and more as a passing of the torch, enabling you to offer help to other people.

Dear study partner,
I am sorry to hear about your loss. It must be hard for you but think about how much your mentor lives on in everything they have taught you and the difference they have made in your life. Not everyone can say that their life benefited others like your mentor benefited yours. They left their mark on this world at least with you and that makes them immortal in a way. I wish you the best.
You got to spend years with a wonderful person. It's hard that they are gone, but I'm sure they equipped you with the tools to move forward, and they'd be proud of you.

You should focus on your father's knee surgery recovery and try not to assume for the worse. Just think, once he is fully recovered from surgery, his knee problems should not be an issue anymore and he will be able to concentrate on his other issues. This surgery is like checking something off his list. You should feel good for him and try to focus on the positives from this. This will get better as he recovers. It is not as bad as you think and that feeling will soon go away. Let him focus on his other health issues.

It's kind of hard to see that, it is a surgery after all and so many things can go wrong, but just know that without this surgery things would be a lot worse. For this surgery will allow your dad to be better and to have more freedom as a human being, this situation is so good because he is getting the work needed to be done to be healthy again. Do not worry this will only make you stronger and it will be something you look back at and laugh. After this your dad will feel better and start his road to recovery.

These type of knee surgeries have become quit routine. While yes it is stressful, if you father wasn't capable of handling the surgery he would not have been a candidate for it. The pain will not be so bad because they will prescribe pain killers for your father after the procedure. Becoming dependent on the pain killers would be a bigger concern for me, over him being able to deal with the pain. Also, if the doctors thought he other health issues would be a problem they would not be willing to preform the operation, he will be fine.

Surgery is scary in general, but try to remember that your father made it through. Although the recovery will be a bit painful, he will be able to move around easier in the future and have overall less pain. He is lucky to have a child that is so concerned and I'm sure you will be there to help him and you both will make it through this stronger.

This recovery process may have unknowns, but think of it this way: Your father is on his way to recovery. And recovery implies a temporary state of difficulty; once one is recovered, they no longer have to endure the pains that caused their original injury.

Once your father's knee replacement is fully healed, he will feel much better. Gone will be the pains associated with having a bad knee, and the disability, the having to take medications, and similar problems. He will be better off for it. Even if there are some complications, they are unlikely to be severe and he will benefit greatly from having a better knee.

It must be hard seeing your father suffer as part of this surgery. However, I think that it's important to keep perspective on the current amount of suffering relative to the good that it will do it over the course of his life. I think that both of you will have a greater quality of life as a result of the surgery, and that you can look beyond the short-term pain to the good times ahead. Do what you can to make recover easier for him, and enjoy your time together.
It will probably be painful in the beginning but once he gets used to the rehabilitation process he will most likely be fine.

The best thing to consider when helping someone who has recently undergone this sort of surgery is that it is going to take time for them to recover. While it is obviously unfortunate that the situation was so serious as to require surgical intervention, at least the procedure is over and the healing process can begin. More than anything, it is important to maintain a positive attitude. While you clearly are concerned for your father, rather than a negative event, try thinking about this as an opportunity to offer support an assistance.
Do what you can to be there for your father while he recovers to help pass the time. Though the recovery process will be painful, it will help to have something to distract him.

It's a long process that's why it's important to just take things one day at a time. Even in those days just take things one at a time and focus on that. He may need help our struggle with one thing but then you can be back to having him resting and recovering for awhile. There's going to be struggles but they are manageable you can get through this, he can get through this. Don't forget why this is going on, the goal is at the end he's going to come out with a better knee than he went in and have a better quality of life. It will be worth it.

I know it's hard to go through these things I have had family as well as friends go through a myriad of different surgeries. The best thing to think about is just how they will have a few days of pain but it will relieve and prevent a lifetime of pain that they have had in the past. I think that it's always important to try to look at the good side in these events.

I know it may seem hard, but try and focus on the fact that your father made it through the surgery without any complications. He is on the road to recovery, and while he may have other health issues, at least the problem with his knee will soon be fixed.

I'm sure he wouldn't want you to worry about his recovery. Try your best to think on the bright side of things.

I hope your dad's knee surgery went well. Surgeries can be tough on someone's body, but one thing I've noticed is that everyone is different when it comes to their recovery and what's involved. It's good that you're aware the recovery process can be painful, especially with your dad's other health issues, but maybe it won't be as bad as you're imagining. While some people do suffer additional pain, not everyone does, especially if they follow the doctor's orders, and your dad might be one of the lucky ones. And once the recovery process is over, he'll have a brand new knee that should last him for years. That's definitely something to look forward to!
Well it may be painful during the recovery for your father in the long run I'm sure his knee will feel better.

That surgery sounds like it was a significant decision. I hope that he heals quickly. In the case of pain and recovery, maybe you could look into ways he can be helped? Most doctors are very understanding of pain suppression, but maybe there are other ways he can control the pain in addition to medication? Also, are there other things that could be done to help your father, such as household assistance, therapy, and so on? Finally, I'm wondering how you're helping yourself during this time. Caring for the carers generally is forgotten but so important.

The knee replacement is going to be a positive change for your Father. It may be a painful recovery but in the end he will be so much better off. You can help him by making sure he stays on top of his pain meds and follows doctor's orders. I'm sure he will get to feeling better before you know it! And he will be more capable to do physical activities too!

This could be a good opportunity for action and reflection. Your dad will need help, so you could see this as a chance to get closer to him and help him out. It's also a good opportunity to think about what this person means to you. You're already past the most stressful part, which is the surgery itself, so now you can take this time choose to use it wisely.
The situation is a stressful situation but your father will feel much better after his knee surgery. He'll be able to move around a lot better and be happier.

The worst part is over. He survived the surgery! Remember, he did the surgery in the first place because his knee was in pain, every single day! As he recovers from this surgery, he is going to feel less pain than ever before and be able to be far more active. You should support him!

Dear study partner,
Although your father's knee replacement may have been stressful and he may have some recovery pain this is a much more positive situation than if he had not had the t
Replacement and was suffering with knee issues. After his initial recovery I'm sure he will be much better and in a lot less pain. I wish him a speedy recovery!
I think you can only let things take their course. Your father probably feels so much better right now. At least there is that.
At least your dreams are telling you whats up so you can fix it.

I think in order to be good at your job you should probably forgo some sleep once in a while. You can make it up another time. Being tired is just part of life and part of working hard at work. It tells you that you are keeping busy and have a lot going on in your life, which is better than being lazy and bored. Use the time you don't sleep to catch up on work and then sleep later when that work is finished and you're confident you can rest and be at ease.

You had a bad dream, while this is not bad by itself per-say it is something to worry about since you said it might have to do with your job. I think this is a wake up call for you to change your career and do something that makes you happy, without adding to much stress to your life. I have hope for you and know that this will improve your life by a lot, take it as a blessing.
Bad dreams my seem tough to get past but just remember it's all in your head.
I am sorry for what you are going through. Keep your head up and I promise things will get better.
You might have had a bad dream but it's good that it led you to wanting to reflect on your current lifestyle.

Dreams help us see our life from a third person perspective. They tend to have little pieces of thoughts you naturally have, so if this is your fear, it's a good indication that you may need to adjust something in your life. Are you getting enough sleep? Can you schedule more time to sleep, if needed? Are you scheduling enough time but still feeling sleepy? Some medical conditions can cause you to feel drained and fatigued.

It was just a dream, and it's pretty common to dream about school or work going wrong. If you're sure you're consistently not getting enough sleep, or you're not sleeping well, you should definitely take this as a sign that it needs to change, not just for your work performance, but for your personal wellbeing.

I'm so sorry that your dream worried you. I find that when I'm having dreams that nag at me, its usually because something is stressing me out that is blending into my unconscious world. It sounds like you might have been worried about your work performance lately and you are tired. Its natural for us to have these thoughts when we're trying to work out a solution in our sleep. When this happens to me, I try to look at it as a positive thing because the situations in the dream haven't actually happened yet. Try to think of it more as an early warning signal from yourself. You have time to try to figure out a plan that will work better to balance your work/personal time.

You should try to practice techniques that can improve your quality of sleep. Doing this can improve your overall well-being and help other parts of your life. This situation isn't permanent and you can do things that will help you fix this.

You can't read to much into dreams. People dream about all kinds of crazy stuff, it doesn't mean your lifestyle is unsustainable. If you really believe you are not getting enough sleep then you could try to do something about it, but I wouldn't assume that because of a dream. Dreams do not have to mean anything and I would guess they usually don't mean anything. If you work performance was suffering you would have gotten some negative feedback from someone about it. I think you're doing just fine.

Trying to make sense of our dreams is something that people have always been attempting throughout time. I would try not to dwell on this dream too much because if you do you will probably continue to have similar dreams. If anything use your dream as a "wakeup call" (no pun intended) and go to bed more early. Change your schedule so you can sleep more. If everyone tried to analyze their dreams and base their lives off of it, we would all be in some serious trouble. Was I really born with a tail or was that dream?
If you get more sleep, it will allow you to feel better throughout the day.

column14: I volunteer to take part in this research
column27: From time to time we all have bad dreams. Dreams often make little or no sense though, and more often than not, are not in and of themselves a reason to worry or something to stress out about. If you are having trouble sleeping look into what may be the true cause of that.

I know you may think that you should change your lifestyle, but this was only a dream. It would be one think if this scenario happened in real life, but it didn't. It seems like you are reading too much into your dream and you should focus more on pushing it out of your mind. People dream crazy things all the time, and most dreams don't have a literal translation.

Sounds like you just need to take a deep breath and relax a bit.

Sometimes dreams are your mind's way of telling you something important and troubling is happening in your life, and sometimes dreams are really just dreams. If you feel fairly energetic at work and are getting good feedback from your boss (or at least no negative feedback), then this dream was probably just a plain, old dream and nothing to worry about. Of course, if you have noticed that you're super tired or rundown at work, then maybe it really is more than a dream, and it might be helpful to pay attention. This might be the way your subconscious is telling you to make some changes.

I know the struggles of getting enough rest at night because I face them as well. What I have found helpful is really just setting a time that you need to be in bed by and forcing yourself to stick to it no matter what. It will help you feel better in the day.

That sounds like a troubling dream! Have you been experiencing extreme tiredness at work in real life? If so what are some things you could do to change that? I know some companies have dedicated nap rooms - would that be an option? Or would simply getting up and moving help? Otherwise, if you are not actually that tired at work, maybe think about if there's something else bothering you? I'm sure trying small changes would help you problem solve the issue at hand.

Perhaps this is an opportunity for you to reexamine your workload and priorities. I think that you have the right idea . . . your body may be telling you that it is reaching its limits. Even if it isn't and you're fully capable of handling the workload, it is an excellent opportunity to make sure that you are maximizing your effectiveness. Take this opportunity to really examine your workday, and don't be afraid to talk with your manager about things that take a lot of time and have little impact.

The first step to fixing a problem is figuring out you have a problem. If you're concerned about not getting enough sleep it may be a bit hard to find the extra time to get some more but it's a simple enough solution in the end. Maybe you have to push a bit of your after work fun to the weekend to get some more sleep during the week but it's doable. There are sleep aids that can help as well or other things people do to help them sleep maybe it's worth looking into.

This seems like your body is prompting you to take a moment and think about how you do things, and it's good that you already seem to be doing that. Things like this happening in life are good moments to try to look at what we're doing from a neutral perspective. Not necessarily from a perspective of whether something is right or wrong, but just seeing if it is what you want. You can channel that sort of energy into making positive changes for yourself.

The dream may seem horrible but it has a silver lining: Your body is telling you that you need more sleep, so you no exactly what your problem is.It might be a good idea to compromise in other areas of your life in order to get more sleep. Do you watch TV later at night? Do you moonlight to pay bills? It might be better to do 10% less work, even if it may make money more tight.

If your job taxes you too much, you might want to consider switching to another one. This is another possible positive avenue for change. Are you otherwise healthy? If so you're already doing better than a lot of other people.

This situation is a lot less permanent than what may seem. You still have some control over it. It's important that you get more sleep so you should be able to figure something out.
You may be tired because you are getting important things done at work. Your work is hopefully being recognized and maybe you will be rewarded for it later.

I have weird dreams all the time. One time I dreamed I was on a rainbow cloud and I found all the characters from Rainbow Brite. Dreams don't always have to mean anything! If you're worried about your lifestyle why not try and slow it down a bit? Go to bed a little earlier or adjust your schedule so you can catch some extra sleep in the mornings? See if that helps. If you haven't gotten any complaints at work, you're probably doing just fine.

Dear study partner,
Everyone has some stress in their lives at one point or another and it is your choice to make whether you think pushing through the stress will be worth it. Your dream could mean that you are experiencing a period of stress that could pass with a little time. I hope things get easier for you!

It is important to consider your feelings about any stressors in your life, so it is appropriate to consider whether or not your dream offers you any insight into your life. It seems like your dream caused you to realize that there is an imbalance of some sort between your work and your leisure time. This is valuable in and of itself, because it can help you decide what is important in your life, and it can also illuminate areas you might want to work on.

Of course, a dream is also just a dream, so you shouldn't feel too distressed about its contents; the average person has between 90 and 150 dreams every month, so some are bound to be less than pleasant, even if they have no actual relation to your life situation.

You should try to find people with similar hobbies with you and strike a conversation with them. Doing this at the performance would be a good time, because you know that they have similar interests as you. Your situation can be improved if you try and meet people that are like you.

column14: I volunteer to take part in this research
column27: We all need alone time sometimes, but at the same time we're social beings and need interaction. It never hurts to reach out to a family member, friend or acquaintance you know who may love to join you, or who may be in the same situation as you. You could also possibly volunteer at soup kitchens or senior centers as so many of these people would absolutely love someone to talk to and join them. There are many ways to fix this situation and instead of feeling down imagine all the good you can do with the activities you can do where you could not just have company for yourself, but also provide company and bring joy to others as well as meet others who could become friends. Enjoy your meals by yourself too, but at least once a weekninvite someone or look into volunteer work, so many people lack company in certain places and you could help too.
Honestly I see nothing wrong with going out by ones self you can enjoy the show and don't have to worry about entertaining anyone else.

I think it's great that you have so much time alone. It's better than being around a bunch of noisy people that are always annoying you and that never give you any privacy. I think you should take advantage of your alone-time and enjoy it. Treat yourself to something special. Enjoy the solitude. Enjoy the performance alone. You can concentrate on it much more easily since you're alone and there's nobody there to disrupt you. Enjoy your alone time while you have it since eventually you will find other people to spend time with and then you will miss the alone time. Treasure it.

Hey I am sorry that you feel alone recently, no one should feel that way. You think it might be bad right now but things are going to change, you obviously want someone to care for and it will happen. Take this time as reflection time and reach inside yourself and really take care of your heart, by the time you start a relationship with someone everything will be all better. Do not worry friend and hang in there.

You don't need to share something with another person in order to enjoy it. If you're feeling lonely, take this as an opportunity to connect with strangers. You might even find someone at the performance to interact with.

Being lonely can be heartbreaking at times, but it doesn't necessarily have to be a permanent thing. You say that it's been a month since you last had dinner with a person, but you will at least be around people at the performance that you are going to. Maybe there will be an after party where you can mix with people. Events with people around are always opportunities to meet others.

Even if nothing comes of this event, at least you will have been around other people. Maybe you can use it as a springboard to attend other events where you will meet more people.

Sometimes we need time alone to really appreciate being around other people that we can converse with. Are you able to reach out to a friend or family member and plan to go see a movie and/or get a bite to eat with in the future? If you put yourself out there and reach out to someone, you'll likely be happily surprised at how many others want to spend time with you.

Being by yourself isn't always so bad. You have a lot less problems and a lot less tension when there is nobody to argue with or disagree with. Eating is about getting nutrients, discussion and companionship are a big over-rated. As for attending a performance, I'm sure you will still enjoy the event even if you are going by yourself. There will be other people you don't know at the performance, maybe you'll make a new friend.

This is not as bad as you may think. No one likes to be alone, but you should consider attempting to make some new friends. I know it is easier said than done, I have the same issue myself sometimes. It is not something that will last forever unless you make it last forever. There are a lot of lonely people out there. I would just try to go meet some new people and if your shy like me, try finding some groups of people online. It is not the end of the world. Take a class somewhere with something you enjoy, I guarantee you will make a new friend.

While it is nice to enjoy events with another person, it is very important that you learn to enjoy being with yourself, and this may be an excellent time in order to rediscover yourself. As an added bonus, other people who are looking for mates would likely find you more attractive if you were comfortable with yourself, as you will come off as somebody that can make them feel more comfortable with themselves.

There are two ways that you can look at this situation. The first, you are lonely and isolated, and are having a difficult time meeting other people to spend time with, which, admittedly, could be distressing. However, another way of looking at the situation is to consider that your evident isolation isn't a problem, but rather an opportunity for you to be independent and on your own.

Instead of seeing the bad in the situation, look at the opportunity you have to pursue your own interests on your own schedule. You may be alone, but that just means that you aren't responsible to spend time with other people when their schedule permits, so you have ample opportunity to do the things that interest you.

I'm so sorry you must so lonely. Have you tried asking anyone to go to a meal with you? I bet someone from work or in your family would be happy to have dinner with you. Seeing a performance sounds like a lot of fun I'm sure someone would be willing to go to that with you if not this time but next time.

Dear study partner,
I know how hard lonliness can be but take this time to think about what you look for in groups of friends or a partner. Maybe this performance will also give you a chance to meet someone new and exciting! Have fun

It definitely sounds like you are feeling lonely. I wonder if there's a way to change that. Is there a reason for being so alone? Did something happen or is it a way you've been feeling? What can you do to start breaking the cycle of loneliness? I know that it is very difficult to break a cycle of entropy, but perhaps there is something small you could do to start feeling like you have options.

When you are feeling lonely the best thing to do is just try to reach out to people. I'm sure there are people in your life that would enjoy having dinner with you or would like to go to a show with you as well. Just reach out and talk to someone and they may be able to come by or go somewhere with you.

I know it may seem difficult to eat out alone, but if you like who you are, then you'll always be in good company. Also you could always get food to go. Or maybe try and introduce yourself to people that are also there alone.

Sometimes it's nice to be with other people, but other times, it's just as nice to spend time alone. Going to this performance by yourself might give you an opportunity to pay more attention to different details and notice more things than if you were there with someone else because you'll be focusing solely on the performance. I find that when I see a performance with another person, I'm often glancing over to check their facial expression to see if they are having the same reaction as me during certain scenes, and it distracts me from the actual performance. And I'm sure your friends or family would love to hear about the performance the next time you see one of them. Sharing information after the fact can be just as exciting as if they were there with you!
Look for people to have dinner with, approach some people and see if they want to hang out with you.
